# BeaverView API — environment variables
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# HOW TO USE
#   1. Copy this file:  cp .env.example .env
#   2. Fill in the values for the systems you want to connect.
#   3. Restart the backend:  ./start.sh
#   4. The connector health badge in the sidebar will turn green automatically.
#
# NEVER commit .env  — it is in .gitignore.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# CREDENTIAL PATTERNS (three types, explained in EDITING-GUIDE.md)
#
#  Pattern 1 — REST API key / OAuth
#    Backend calls the service directly using the key.
#    Browser never sees the credential.
#    Used by: Fusion, 25Live, ServiceNow
#
#  Pattern 2 — Device web proxy
#    Backend reverse-proxies device web UIs (XPanel, WattBox, PTZ cameras).
#    The device IP lives only in the backend. Browser accesses /api/proxy/...
#    Used by: Crestron XPanel, WattBox, PTZ cameras
#
#  Pattern 3 — OSU Entra SSO passthrough
#    The device/service already accepts OSU Azure AD / SAML login.
#    Backend builds a context-aware URL; user's existing OSU session handles auth.
#    Used by: ScreenConnect, SharePoint, ServiceNow (web UI)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ── CRESTRON DIRECT DEVICE POLLING  (Pattern 2 — device HTTP API) ────────────
# BeaverView polls each Crestron control processor directly over HTTP/HTTPS
# using its built-in REST API (4-Series: CH5 REST; 3-Series: XPanel heartbeat).
# Device IPs are stored in the device_ips table — import them from the
# Hardware IP spreadsheet using:  python3 import_device_ips.py
#
# These credentials are the shared admin account for all processors.
# If processors use individual passwords, implement per-room lookup in main.py.
#
# CRESTRON_POLL_USERNAME=admin
# CRESTRON_POLL_PASSWORD=your-crestron-admin-password
# CRESTRON_POLL_INTERVAL_SECONDS=60
#
# Set to "false" to accept self-signed certificates on processors (recommended
# for internal networks where processors use factory-default certs):
# CRESTRON_VERIFY_SSL=false


# ── 25LIVE / COLLEGENET  (Pattern 1 — REST API) ───────────────────────────────
# 25Live provides the room scheduling calendar (what event is in each room now).
# Use a service account, not a personal account.
#
# LIVE25_BASE_URL=https://25live.collegenet.com/25live/data/oregonstate
# LIVE25_USERNAME=svc-beaverview@oregonstate.edu
# LIVE25_PASSWORD=your-service-account-password


# ── SCREENCONNECT  (Pattern 3 — Entra SSO passthrough) ────────────────────────
# ScreenConnect already accepts OSU Azure AD login.
# The backend only needs the base URL to build machine-specific session links.
# No credentials are stored here — the user's OSU browser session handles auth.
#
# SC_BASE_URL=https://screenconnect.oregonstate.edu


# ── WATTBOX / OVRC  (Pattern 1 + Pattern 2) ───────────────────────────────────
# OvrC (the WattBox cloud platform) has a REST API for outlet status and cycling.
# For the detailed outlet web UI, the backend proxies the device's local web server.
#
# WATTBOX_OVRC_BASE_URL=https://my.ovrc.com/api/v1
# WATTBOX_OVRC_API_KEY=your-ovrc-api-key
#
# For direct device access on the local network (no OvrC cloud):
# WATTBOX_DIRECT_USERNAME=admin
# WATTBOX_DIRECT_PASSWORD=your-wattbox-password


# ── CRESTRON XPANEL  (Pattern 2 — device web proxy) ──────────────────────────
# XPanel is a web app served directly from each Crestron control processor.
# The backend fetches it from the device IP and proxies it to the browser.
# Credentials are the same admin account on every CP (or use the room's specific creds).
#
# CRESTRON_PROXY_USERNAME=admin
# CRESTRON_PROXY_PASSWORD=your-crestron-admin-password


# ── PTZ CAMERAS  (Pattern 2 — device web proxy) ───────────────────────────────
# PTZOptics cameras have a built-in HTTP API for pan/tilt/zoom commands.
# The backend sends HTTP GET requests to the camera IP on the tech's behalf.
# Camera IPs come from the Hardware IP spreadsheet (never stored in this repo).
#
# PTZ_PROXY_USERNAME=admin
# PTZ_PROXY_PASSWORD=your-ptz-admin-password


# ── SERVICENOW  (Pattern 1 — OAuth client credentials) ────────────────────────
# ServiceNow accepts OAuth 2.0 client credentials for server-to-server calls.
# Create a dedicated OAuth application record in your SN instance.
# The web UI version (opening a pre-filled form) uses Pattern 3 (Entra SSO).
#
# SERVICENOW_INSTANCE=oregonstate
# SERVICENOW_CLIENT_ID=your-client-id
# SERVICENOW_CLIENT_SECRET=your-client-secret


# ── SHAREPOINT  (Pattern 3 — Entra SSO passthrough) ──────────────────────────
# SharePoint is part of O365 — users are already logged in via OSU Entra.
# Backend only needs the base URL to build room-type document library links.
#
# SHAREPOINT_BASE_URL=https://oregonstate.sharepoint.com/sites/AVSupport


# ── OSU AZURE / ENTRA SSO  (Phase 8 — BeaverView login) ──────────────────────
# When you're ready to add real login, register BeaverView as an app in
# Azure Portal → App registrations. Assign the two groups below in
# Azure → Enterprise Applications → BeaverView → Users and groups.
#
# AZURE_TENANT_ID=your-osu-tenant-id
# AZURE_CLIENT_ID=your-app-client-id
# AZURE_CLIENT_SECRET=your-app-client-secret
#
# Group object IDs (find in Azure AD → Groups):
# AZURE_GROUP_TECHNICIAN=object-id-of-technician-group
# AZURE_GROUP_ADMIN=object-id-of-admin-group


# ── DEVICE PROXY SECRET ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Random string used to sign short-lived proxy tokens.
# Generate one with:  python3 -c "import secrets; print(secrets.token_hex(32))"
#
# PROXY_SECRET=your-random-secret-here
